125· 8. et somno coniventibus etc. The reading of the Mss. in this 14³ passage contains so gross a violation of grammatical construction that it is difficult to believe that Cicero really wrote it so. After coniventibus, whether taken as abl. abs. or dat, a clause ought to follow with some other subject than oculi ,· such is not the case, but instead os it comes utque quiescerent. Nothing can be madeus this utque, or ut qui as sorne Mss. have it; it must have crept in through an oversight. But the copyists, misled by the preceding apertis, have written corriventibus instead of coni· ventes (coniventeis) sc. oculi, as Cicero wrote; in this way we gain the necessary subject to quiescerent.
